{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"997889e7-1d10-48bc-af00-8990432ed2a1","content":"Here's my analysis of the three evaluation performance anti-patterns in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **File I/O Property Function** (EvalHeavy.csproj, line 13) — **High Impact**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via `System.IO.File` during evaluation is expensive. This runs on *every* evaluation — including IDE design-time builds (which happen frequently). **Fix:** Move this to a target that runs at build time, or read it via a custom task.\n\n### 2. **Overly Broad Glob** (EvalHeavy.csproj, line 9) — **High Impact**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` recursively walks the entire directory tree. It only excludes `bin`/`obj`, so it will scan into `.git`, `node_modules`, `packages`, or any other large subdirectory. **Fix:** Use a narrower pattern (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or add heavy directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`:\n```xml\n<DefaultItemExcludes>$(DefaultItemExcludes);node_modules\\**;.git\\**</DefaultItemExcludes>\n```\n\n### 3. **Chained Import Depth** (imports/) — **Low Impact (but a smell)**\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level chain isn't critical on its own (problems start around 20+), but each import adds evaluation overhead. This pattern tends to grow over time. Consider flattening or importing directly.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The biggest wins come from removing the `File::ReadAllText` property function and narrowing the `**\\*.*` glob. Both execute during every evaluation pass, including frequent IDE background builds.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4573a7c9-03e3-47fb-8692-b2d330d55536","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze it for MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nThe issues I can see:\n\n1. **File I/O property function during evaluation** (line 13): `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` — This reads a file during evaluation, which is expensive. Every evaluation (including design-time builds in Visual Studio) pays this cost.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern** (line 9): `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` — This walks the entire directory tree. The `**\\*.*` glob is very broad and will recursively scan all directories. If the project directory contains large folders (like `node_modules`, `.git`, etc.), this could be very slow. Also, it doesn't use `DefaultItemExcludes` to skip known heavy directories.\n   \n3. **Deep import chain** (lines 6, level1→level2→level3): There's a 3-level deep import chain here. While that's not extreme compared to the >20 level warning threshold, it's still adding evaluation overhead that could compound if the chain grows further.","outputTokens":789,"requestId":"0401:20E780:5E3BF52:671F244:69F01078"},"id":"845b7b9c-916a-49e1-ac3d-f3e2fe0f6b34","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:42:33.199Z","parentId":"2ac124bd-2010-4541-a614-07266fcb4df6"}
